(1, 'The Swimmer', 'In Place', '1977-01-01', 'Vancouver Aquatic Centre', '1050 Beach Avenue', 'An abstract form representing the motion of swimming, this bronze sculpture is mounted on two poles in front of the Aquatic Centre.', 'Commissioned by Duncan McNab and Associates, architects, and the engineering firm working on the Aquatic Centre.', '49.276990', '-123.135029', 'Silicon bronze', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=2&ImageId=2', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=2', 1, 1, 1),
(2, 'George Cunningham Memorial Sundial', 'In Place', '1967-01-01', 'English Bay', 'Beach Avenue & Denman Street', 'A classic bronze sundial sits on top of a 4\'5\" high rectangular granite pedestal engraved with abstract modernist geometric designs.  A second edition of the sundial was commissioned for the VanDusen Gardens around 1972.', 'Erected under the auspices of the Centennial Committee of Vancouver in cooperation with the Parks Board, the sculpture was presented to the City by Cunningham Drug Stores Ltd. whose first store was opened at Denman and Nelson Streets in 1911.  The inscription reads, \" I mark my hours by shadow, mayest thou mark thine by sunshine.\" The sundial commemorates three English \"greenhorns\" - Samual Brighouse, John Morton, and William Hailstone who in 1862 filed the first land claim and planned the first home and industry in the then heavily wooded area now bounded by Burrard Inlet, Stanley Park, English Bay and Burrard Street to which they received title in 1867.', '49.287577', '-123.141787', 'Bronze, stone, granite', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=3&ImageId=3', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=3', 1, 1, 1),
(3, 'Two Steel and Copper Fountains', 'In Place', '1965-01-01', 'Beach Towers Apartments', '1600 Beach Avenue', 'Two copper ship-like abstract forms grace a pool of green water at this apartment dwelling.', NULL, '49.284080', '-123.142216', 'Steel & copper, mosaic tile', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=4&ImageId=4', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=4', 1, 2, 2),
(4, 'Untitled (Clydemont Centre)', 'In Place', '1949-01-01', 'Clydemont Centre', '307 West Broadway', 'An elegant figurative relief in nouveau modernist style depicts nature and industry and stands out against a corrugated background surface. The building was formerly the Vancouver Labour Temple. The image is based on the wheel of industry and the figures include people engaged in different kinds of work, airplanes, buildings, plants, birds, and animals on a background of sun rays.', NULL, '49.263263', '-123.111389', 'Stone', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=5&ImageId=5', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=5', 2, 2, 3),
(5, 'Untitled', 'In Place', '1968-01-01', NULL, '625 Bute Street', NULL, NULL, '49.287929', '-123.124400', 'Paint', NULL, 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=6', 3, 2, 1),
(6, 'Sidewalk Mosaic', 'In Place', '1965-01-01', 'Mini Park', 'Burrard & Hastings Street', 'mosaic', NULL, '49.287305', '-123.117000', 'Rock, metal', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=7&ImageId=6', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=7', 3, 1, 4),
(7, 'Charles Bentall', 'In Place', '1977-01-01', 'Bentall Bldg.', '501 Burrard Street', 'This classic bust depicts the entrepreneur Charles Bentall who died in 1974.', NULL, '49.286828', '-123.117800', 'Bronze', NULL, 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=8', 3, 2, 5),
(8, 'Ksan Mural', 'In Place', '1972-01-01', 'Royal Bank', '1025 West Georgia at Burrard', 'This beautiful 9-panel frieze was carved in red cedar and painted by five artists over a period of three months. It depicts  the Gitksan mythical character Weget (Man-Raven), who created our world through his mischievous activities. The Gitksan people live near the Bulkley and Skeena Rivers in north central BC. According to a brochure published by the Royal Bank, the 3 central panels represent various myths: In one, Raven disguises himself in the skin of a deer in order to steal fire from the humans (shown as small faces in the lower corners). In the second story, Raven goes through a hole in the sky to steal the sun. The image depicts the sun (central to the panel) clutched in his claws over the box he put it in. As the story goes, he dropped the box in his haste and that\'s how light came to the world. Other creatures (salmon and seal) are depicted around his wings. In the third panel, Raven attempts to capture a fish to eat. As the fish struggles to get away, his head becomes misshapen and that\'s how the bullhead fish came to be. The side panels represent specific totem creatures: the frog, the wolf, the killer whale, the owl, the human and the bear.', NULL, '49.284867', '-123.121201', 'Red cedar', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=9&ImageId=7', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=9', 3, 2, 3),
(9, 'Untitled', 'In Place', '1954-01-01', 'Mercantile Bank', '540 Burrard Street', NULL, NULL, '49.286289', '-123.118500', 'Painting on linen', NULL, 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=10', 3, 2, 6),
(10, 'Asclepius', 'In Place', '1951-01-01', 'College of Physicians & Surgeons of B.C.', '1807 West 10th Avenue', NULL, NULL, '49.262865', '-123.145985', 'Concrete, steel', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=11&ImageId=8', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=11', 4, 2, 3),
(11, 'Rainforest', 'In Place', '1986-01-01', 'On loan to The Reach Gallery in Abbotsford', NULL, 'Rainforest is a tilted steel platform with 28 steel poles meant to represent a forest of trees and also the driving rain. There are  silhouettes of objects like and axe, cross saw, chairs, etc, interspersed among the poles.  Rainforest was loaned to The Reach Gallery in Abbotsford as part of its exhibition on trees.', 'Rainforest was designed in response to a call for public outdoor sculptures to be constructed and exhibited at Expo ‘86 in Vancouver. The piece was fabricated in Vanier Park during the summer of 1986 where visitors were invited to watch the construction process and interact with the artist.  The piece primarily consists of numerous parallel steel pipes intended to provide the sense of driving rain. Attached to many of these angled rain-like elements are shorter smaller pipes producing a simplified tree forms.   Interspersed among the pipe components are various objects associated with forestry; a crosscut saw, a baseball bat, a ladder, a house, all set at the identical angle to the tree branches.The intention is to merge the visual sense of driving rain with trees and objects associated with forestry. Excessive repetition causes the piece to appear both chaotic and ordered.  Hopefully viewers can focus on any one of, or all of these elements simultaneously.', NULL, NULL, 'Steel', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=12&ImageId=9', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=12', 5, 1, 1),
(12, 'Untitled', 'In Place', '1959-01-01', 'Queen Elizabeth Theatre', '649 Cambie Street', NULL, NULL, '49.280537', '-123.112600', 'Metal & enamel', NULL, 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=13', 3, 1, 1),
(13, 'Untitled', 'In Place', '1962-01-01', 'Queen Elizabeth Playhouse', '649 Cambie Street', NULL, NULL, '49.280558', '-123.112600', 'Canvas', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=14&ImageId=10', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=14', 3, 1, 7),
(14, 'Cycle of Flowering', 'Removed', '1959-01-01', 'Queen Elizabeth Theatre (Downtown)', '649 Cambie Street (Downtown)', NULL, NULL, '49.280222', '-123.112870', 'Paint', NULL, 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=15', 5, 1, 6),
(15, 'Untitled', 'Removed', '1970-01-01', 'Plaza 500 Hotel', 'Cambie & 12th Avenue', NULL, NULL, '49.260104', '-123.115462', 'Concrete, glass', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=16&ImageId=11', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=16', 2, 2, 3),
(16, 'Stations of the Cross', 'In Place', '1964-01-01', 'Holy Name Parish', '4925 Cambie Street', NULL, NULL, '49.240719', '-123.119119', 'Lead', NULL, 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=17', 6, 2, 1),
(17, 'Gerald Grattan McGeer', 'In Place', '1948-01-01', 'Vancouver City Hall', '453 West 12th Avenue at Cambie', 'This is a classic bronze bust of the former mayor of Vancouver in official regalia.', 'Chuck Davis called Gerry McGeer a \"human bulldozer\" in an article in the Vancouver Sun  In his first week as mayor of Vancouer, he confiscated 1000 slot machines around the city. He was mayor during the1935 demonstration by unemployed workers in the downtown eastside and was instrumental in building city hall on its 12th Avenue site. He died during his second term as mayor in 1947. (Vancouver Sun, April 7, 2001,H5)', '49.260687', '-123.113718', 'Bronze', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=18&ImageId=12', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=18', 2, 1, 5),
