(125, 'Al of the Gispudwada (Black Bear Crest of the Killer Whale Tribe)', 'In Place', '1976-01-01', 'VanDusen Botanical Garden', '5251 Oak Street', 'This Gitksan pole of red cedar was commissioned by the VanDusen Botanical Gardens Association. It incorporates the following figures and legend: human form at the top - a hunter who went into the mountains, was captured by a black bear, and assumed the bear form; human head in the top figure\'s stomach - a friendly villager who assisted \"Bear Man\" to resume his human form when everyone else abandoned him; the bear figure at bottom represents \"Bear Man\" before being turned back into human form; the human head in bear\'s stomach indicates that bear figure is \"Bear Man\" (from VanDusen Garden website)', NULL, '49.239068', '-123.134604', 'Red cedar', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=140&ImageId=109', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=140', 9, 1, 10),
