(150, 'Whaling Wall VIII', 'Removed', '1985-01-01', 'Wyland Bldg. (Downtown)', '1190 Melville Street (Downtown)', 'The large mural covers the side of the building in blues and greys and features a pod of Orca Whales on the northern BC coast.', 'The piece honours the Sea Shepard Society and was commissioned to aid in the education and protection of endangered animals.', '49.287533', '-123.124284', 'Paint on concrete', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=168&ImageId=137', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=168', 3, 2, 6),
(151, 'Girl Waiting for a Bus', 'In Place', '1962-01-01', 'Parkview Towers', 'Burrard & Cornwall Street', 'Apt\'s first sculpture, it was offered for sale to the Park Board which declined. It was purchased privately for Parkview Towers in 1962.  In 1967 it was smashed by vandals but later repaired.', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Concrete, painted white', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=169&ImageId=138', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=169', 4, 2, 1),
(152, 'The Builders', 'In Place', '1986-01-01', 'Discovery Park', 'Burrard & Dunsmuir Street', 'A black granite sculpture made of three blocks. It is the artist\'s impression of a person in prayer using simple, strong forms.', '\"The sculpture is a tribute to the immigrants who settled in Canada.\" It was carved for the City Shapes Sculpture Symposium for Vancouver\'s centennial in 1986.', '49.285633', '-123.120121', 'Black Quebec granite', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=170&ImageId=139', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=170', 3, 6, 1),
(153, 'Vessel', 'In Place', '1986-01-01', 'Discovery Park', 'Burrard & Dunsmuir Street', 'The sculpture is made of abstract geometric forms and constructed to suggest a ship. It sits on the grass outside the downtown skytrain station.', NULL, '49.285603', '-123.120043', 'Granite', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=171&ImageId=1110', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=171', 3, 6, 1),
(154, 'Inukshuk', 'In Place', '1986-01-01', 'English Bay', 'Bidwell and shoreline walk', 'Built of stacked granite blocks in a human form, Inukshuks are symbols of welcome in the north.  This one weighs 31,500 kg. It is built of gigantic rocks and stands 6 meters high.', 'The welcoming figure was made on the Inuit model for the NWT pavillion designed by Bing Thom  and \"shaped like a five-story igloo\" at Expo 86.  The figure was sited at English Bay after the fair. The stones were brought in from a quarry in the Fraser Valley and then shaped and stacked by crane and pinned together with rebar. Inukshuks in the north are usually much smaller and the rocks are balanced on each other.  They act as sign posts or distance markers that can be seen on the flat horizon. Artist Kanak said,  \"By a lake an Inukshuk means lots of fish.\"  The figure is a \"reminder of the ingenuity of my people in addressing transportation and communications challenges prior to the introduction of modern technology.\" (sources: M.Farrow, V.Sun, April 24, 1985; V.Province, May 5, 1985)', '49.284323', '-123.143704', 'Granite boulders', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=172&ImageId=141', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=172', 1, 1, 1),
(155, 'Fountain of the Pioneers', 'In Place', '1969-01-01', 'Bentall Bldg.', '500 Burrard Street', 'Water splashes down two levels of this abstract rounded form and into the pool below. The sculpture is the centre piece of the long rectangular pool in front of the Bentall towers.', '\"..my fountain sculptures are an attempt to unify water--the life force of the universe that flows in an elusive cyclical course throughout eternity--with an immutable metal sculpture.\"', '49.286242', '-123.117820', 'Bronze', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=173&ImageId=142', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=173', 3, 2, 2),
(156, 'Untitled (Shanghai lions)', 'In Place', '1995-01-01', 'North Main Street overpass to Port Authority', NULL, 'a pair of carved granite lions', 'A gift from the Port of Shanghai to the Port of Vancouver in recognition of their sisterhood relationship. The lions are traditionally placed at an important gateway to provide peace and prosperity.', '49.284804', '-123.099243', 'Granite', NULL, 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=174', 3, 5, 1),
(157, 'Symbols of the Cuneiforms', 'In Place', '1960-01-01', NULL, '750 Burrard Street', 'This artwork is a delicate metal relief with plexiglas inserts.  The white sections are lighted at night. It is mounted on the exterior northwest corner of the building at Burrard and Robson (formerly the Vancouver Public Library). The piece was saved when the building was renovated from the old library.', NULL, '49.283618', '-123.122020', 'Metal, plexiglass', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ImageDisplay.aspx?AreaId=175&ImageId=143', 'https://covapp.vancouver.ca/PublicArtRegistry/ArtworkDetail.aspx?ArtworkId=175', 3, 2, 1),
